The average daily maximum temperature hovers around a scorching 38.1 °C (100.6 °F) annually, frequently exceeding 40 °C (104 °F) during the hotter months, peaking at an almost unbearable 43.3 °C (109.9 °F) in June. Record highs push even further into the realm of the truly extreme, reaching 47.0 °C (116.6 °F). The mean daily minimum temperatures rarely offer significant relief, staying well above 19 °C (66 °F) even in the "cooler" months.

[Precipitation](/Precipitation), predictably, is minimal, with an annual average of only 208.5 mm (8.2 inches). The majority of this meager rainfall occurs during a brief and unreliable wet season, primarily in August, which receives the highest average at 84.6 mm (3.33 inches). For much of the year, the landscape endures prolonged periods of intense aridity, a brutal reality that shapes every aspect of life, from agriculture to the very architecture designed to combat the ceaseless heat. Building a city, let alone a capital, in such conditions is less an act of urban planning and more a defiance of nature itself.

